    "body": "### Problem\n\n#2325 has been open for the past ~9 years and while the workaround given in that issue is serviceable, it doesn't replicate the functionality of Vim since it's dependent on mouse release (so it wouldn't work if left mousebutton was double clicked):\r\n```\r\nset mouse=a\r\nvmap <LeftRelease> \"*ygv\r\n```\r\nAfter a bit of discussion on Discord, `@origamiduck` was able to come up with a solution that achieves autoselect very well as far as I have tested:\r\n```lua\r\nvim.api.nvim_create_autocmd(\"CursorMoved\", {\r\n  desc = \"Keep * synced with selection\",\r\n  callback = function()\r\n    local mode = vim.fn.mode(false)\r\n    if mode == \"v\" or mode == \"V\" or mode == \"^V\" then\r\n      vim.cmd([[silent norm \"*ygv]])\r\n    end\r\n  end,\r\n})\r\n```\r\nI wanted to post this workaround here so others can find it since Discord is not indexable by search engines. Thanks again to `origamiduck` for coming up with this. I understand this is a low priority feature but I hope this well help other people searching for a solution until Vim's autoselect is implemented in Neovim.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nThe issue is well known and can be replicated as follows\r\n* Select text within neovim using either the mouse or the keyboard (in visual mode) on a graphical (X or Wayland) Linux system\r\n* Middle click in a text field outside of neovim\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThe expected behavior should mirror Vim's `clipboard=autoselect` as described in #2325\n\n### Neovim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.9.5\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nVim (9.1) doesn't have this issue\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nDebian GNU/Linux with Xorg 7.7+23\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nxterm 390-1\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nGitHub Releases",
